4.1.3 METHODS
A. Direct Voltage Method:
‚Ä¢ Measures the open-circuit or stabilized terminal voltage using a voltage divider.
‚Ä¢ Converts voltage to SoC using a calibrated lookup table or polynomial regression based on 
battery discharge curves.
‚Ä¢ Suitable for rest periods or low-current load states.
B. Coulomb Counting Method:
‚Ä¢ Uses a current sensor (ACS712) to measure current in/out of the battery.
‚Ä¢ Integrates current over time using the relation:
ùëÜùëúùê∂(ùë°) = ùëÜùëúùê∂(ùë° ‚àí 1) +
ùêº(ùë°)
ùëÑùëõ
‚àÜùë°
‚Ä¢ Periodically corrected using voltage-based estimation to reduce drift.
11
C. Kalman Filter Method:
‚Ä¢ Implements a discrete-time Kalman Filter algorithm.
‚Ä¢ Predicts the next SoC based on battery model and updates it using sensor measurements 
(voltage/current).
‚Ä¢ Reduces noise and measurement error, suitable for dynamic and non-linear conditions.
D. IoT Communication:
‚Ä¢ ESP32/ESP8266 module sends SoC values to cloud servers like ThingSpeak via Wi-Fi.
‚Ä¢ Real-time battery status can be accessed on mobile apps or web interfaces.
‚Ä¢ Enables alerts and trend visualization.
